  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are typically also malleable. In fact, these properties often go hand in hand:\n\n1. Ductility is the ability of a metal to be drawn or stretched into a thin wire without breaking.\n\n2. Malleability is the ability of a metal to be hammered or pressed into thin sheets without fracturing.\n\nBoth properties are related to the metallic bonding and crystal structure of metals, which allows atoms to slide past each other without destroying the material's integrity. Some metals that are both ductile and malleable include:\n\n- Gold\n- Silver\n- Copper\n- Aluminum\n- Platinum\n\nThe degree of ductility and malleability can vary between different metals, but generally, metals that are ductile are also malleable to some extent.",
